    "narrative": "Today\u2019s slate for LawDog centers on two high-floor anchors: **Cal Raleigh** (71.30) and **Geraldo Perdomo** (68.05). **Cal Raleigh** benefits from a premium spot in the two-hole against a softer Liberatore matchup, with his efficiency bolstered by strong xwOBA metrics and a clear platoon advantage. Meanwhile, **Geraldo Perdomo** earns his elite status through a favorable pairing against M\u00e1rquez; his leadoff role combined with a substantial 19% SP skill edge makes him our primary catalyst for counting stats today. **Bryson Stott** (66.12) and **Jonathan Aranda** (65.19) also provide excellent stability, both benefiting from significant platoon-driven ceiling boosts that elevate them well into the \"Strong\" start tier.\n\nWe are keeping a close eye on the Eury P\u00e9rez matchup, which drives high-efficiency scoring for **Matt Chapman**, **Luis Arraez**, **Drew Gilbert**, and **Jung Hoo Lee**. While **Luis Arraez** and **Matt Chapman** occupy the heart of the order, their scores are buoyed by a wind-out scenario at the park and a slow opposing delivery that significantly enhances our stolen base potential\u2014a critical factor for our internal weighting. Conversely, **Taylor Ward** faces a high-variance test against Crochet; while his raw score (59.46) is solid, the 19% penalty against the pitcher\u2019s skill is partially mitigated by a massive 16% park factor, keeping him in the lineup despite the elite opposition.\n\nThe most difficult bench decision involved **Wenceel Perez**, whose 44.34 score fell just short of the threshold. While he benefits from positive park and SP skill factors, a negative platoon adjustment and a bottom-third order placement ultimately moved him behind **Drew Gilbert** in the final configuration. Investors should note the risk surrounding **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez**; despite a respectable 59.41 score, his poor BvP history (29 PA) against Gausman is a notable drag on his projection. We have prioritized lineup efficiency over pure talent today to maximize our 5x5 categories, though we remain wary of the strikeout potential presented by the high-velocity arms in the matchups for **Daulton Varsho** and **Taylor Ward**.",
